Besprechung¶

1. Recap: Bug bei der Mean Berechnung ("falsche" Koef.-Matrix)¶

  • Spezifizierte Basis und tatsächlich geschätzte Basis unterscheiden sich bei der Verwendung von mgcv.
  • mgcv nimmt die spezifizierte Basis und implementiert noch einen "sum-to-one" constraint. Die ausgegebenen Koeffizienten gehören zur constrainten Basis.
  • Die "richtigen" Koeffizienten müssen über entsprechende Basis-Trafo DD aus den constrainten Koeffizienten rekonstruiert werden: ^Σ=D⋅^~ΣΣ^=D⋅Σ~^.
  • DD wird leider nicht von mgcv mitgeliefert sondern muss extra berechnet werden über X=D⋅~XX=D⋅X~, mit X,~XX,X~ Design- und constrained Designmatrix.

Ergebnisse sehen jetzt deutlich besser aus. Vor allem auch für höhere Penalties! :)

2. Smooth Procrustes Fits¶

^p(t)=b(t)T^θp^(t)=b(t)Tθ^ estimated Procrustes mean function, qq piecewise constant SRV transform with q|[tj,tj+1]=qj∈Cq|[tj,tj+1]=qj∈C.

For estimation of the Procrustes fits we need to estimate two scalar products:

^qp=⟨q,^p⟩⟨q,q⟩qq^p=⟨q,p^⟩⟨q,q⟩q

2.1 Piecewise constant approximation¶

So far I treat qq as piecewise constant (as in Lisa's paper):

⟨q,^p⟩=∫10⟨q(t),^p(t)⟩dt≈m−1∑j=0∫tj+1tj⟨qj,^p(t)⟩dt⟨q,p^⟩=∫01⟨q(t),p^(t)⟩dt≈∑j=0m−1∫tjtj+1⟨qj,p^(t)⟩dt⟨q,q⟩=∫10⟨q(t),q(t)⟩dt≈m−1∑j=0(tj+1−tj)⟨qj,qj⟩⟨q,q⟩=∫01⟨q(t),q(t)⟩dt≈∑j=0m−1(tj+1−tj)⟨qj,qj⟩

2.2 Smooth approximation¶

Idea: Smooth qq in mean basis b(t)b(t), so that ^q(t)=b(t)T^θqq^(t)=b(t)Tθ^q. Then the scalar products simplify to ⟨q,^p⟩≈^θHqG^θ⟨q,p^⟩≈θ^qHGθ^ ⟨q,q⟩≈^θHqG^θq⟨q,q⟩≈θ^qHGθ^q

As qq can be sparse, we may want to use the estimated covariance matrix ^ΞΞ^ when estimating θqθq in the form of a Normal prior θq∼NCk(0,^Ξ)θq∼NCk(0,Ξ^) leading to

^θq=(BTB+Ξ−1)−1BTqθ^q=(BTB+Ξ−1)−1BTq

or equivalently using eigendecompositon Ξ=VΛV−1Ξ=VΛV−1 with VHV=IVHV=I and Λ=diag(λ1,…,λk)Λ=diag(λ1,…,λk)

^θq=V(VHBTBV+Λ−1)−1VHBTqθ^q=V(VHBTBV+Λ−1)−1VHBTq

In general how well this works tends to depend on how close the curve is to the estimated mean.

Maybe using a penalty parameter - controling the strength of the regularization - is also thinkable? Something like this:

^θq(λ)=V(VHBTBV+λ⋅Λ−1)−1VHBTqθ^q(λ)=V(VHBTBV+λ⋅Λ−1)−1VHBTq

Thought: A normal prior is probably not appropriate, because while its true that E[θ]=0E[θ]=0 (due to rotational symmetry) I would think that in general E[∥θ∥]≠0E[‖θ‖]≠0. A distribution more like a Normal distribution lying on a ring around 0 with radius r=∥θ∥r=‖θ‖ is probably better? Then estimates wouldn't be pressed to zero so strongly, and instead would be pressed to curve of size equal to the mean.

3. Closed means¶

Mean p(t)=b(t)Tθp(t)=b(t)Tθ with b(t)b(t) being B-spline basis functions with corresponding Gram matrix GG.

Then the procrustes mean in an orthogonal basis is the solution to optimization problem:

^θ=argmaxθ∈CkθHG^ΞGθs.t.θHGθ=1θ^=arg⁡maxθ∈CkθHGΞ^Gθs.t.θHGθ=1

For a closed mean, we additionally want that ||^μ(1)−^μ(0)||2=0||μ^(1)−μ^(0)||2=0. We can rewrite this on SRV level as

∥^μ(1)−^μ(0)∥2=∥∥∥∫10^p(t)∥^p(t)∥dt∥∥∥2‖μ^(1)−μ^(0)‖2=‖∫01p^(t)‖p^(t)‖dt‖2

It would be nice to write this restriction as a function of θθ. Maybe like this?

∥∥∥∫10b(t)Tθ∥b(t)Tθ∥dt∥∥∥2??DU,b(t)≥0≤∥∥∥∫10b(t)Tθb(t)Tθ∥⋅∥dt∥∥∥2=∥∥∥∫10θTb(t)b(t)Tθ∥⋅∥dt∥∥∥2=∥∥∥θT∫10b(t)b(t)Tdtθ∥⋅∥∥∥∥2‖∫01b(t)Tθ‖b(t)Tθ‖dt‖2≤??DU,b(t)≥0‖∫01b(t)Tθb(t)Tθ‖⋅‖dt‖2=‖∫01θTb(t)b(t)Tθ‖⋅‖dt‖2=‖θT∫01b(t)b(t)Tdtθ‖⋅‖‖2=∥∥θTGθ∥⋅∥∥∥2=∥∥θT∥⋅∥Gθ∥∥2=θHGθ∥⋅∥θT∥⋅∥Gθ=‖θTGθ‖⋅‖‖2=‖θ‖⋅‖TGθ‖2=θHGθ‖⋅‖θ‖⋅‖TGθ

Maybe the term θ∥⋅∥θT∥⋅∥θ‖⋅‖θ‖⋅‖T can be simplified or bound from above further?

With estimated coefficient matrix ^ΞΞ^, so that ^C(s,t)=b(s)T^Ξb(t)C^(s,t)=b(s)TΞ^b(t) is closed, we end up with the optimization problem for the closed mean:

^θ=argmaxθ∈CkθHG^ΞGθs.t.θHGθ=1andθHGθ∥⋅∥θT∥⋅∥Gθ=0θ^=arg⁡maxθ∈CkθHGΞ^Gθs.t.θHGθ=1andθHGθ‖⋅‖θ‖⋅‖TGθ=0
